Benchmark: FrontierScience-Olympiad
Domain: physics

Full problem:
Suppose the Moon is 3 degrees above the horizon and we observe it over the ocean that has small ripples on its surface. We are located such that we can see the reflection of the moon in the ocean. Assume we are very far away from the ocean. Derive a value for the quantity `\( r \)` defined as a ratio of the perceived maximum vertical displacement over the perceived maximum horizontal displacement of the shape of the Moon's reflection in the ocean, by using ray geometry. Round your answer to the nearest whole number.

Think step by step and solve the problem below. At the end of your response, write your final answer on a new line starting with “FINAL ANSWER”. It should be an answer to the question such as providing a number, mathematical expression, formula, or entity name, without any extra commentary or providing multiple answer attempts.

Candidate v2 hierarchy:
{
  "global": "Derive the ratio of vertical to horizontal displacement of the Moon's reflection in rippling ocean water using ray geometry at grazing incidence angle.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Analyze ray geometry for moon at grazing incidence (3° above horizon)",
      "atomics": [
        "Set up coordinate system with moon incident rays at angle θ=3° to horizontal",
        "Calculate surface normal perturbations from ripple slopes",
        "Determine reflected ray direction changes for small surface tilts"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Establish constraints on ripple slopes from ray propagation",
      "atomics": [
        "Determine maximum ripple slope that keeps reflected rays traveling upward to observer",
        "Compute angular deviation of reflected rays as 2×(slope magnitude)",
        "Apply constraint that ray z-component must remain positive for observer at height above water"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Relate angular spreading to linear displacements at grazing incidence",
      "atomics": [
        "Establish that vertical ripples (in line-of-sight direction) constrain the z-component of reflected rays",
        "Establish that horizontal ripples (perpendicular to line-of-sight) affect lateral ray components",
        "Account for projection effects of grazing-incidence viewing geometry"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Calculate the ratio of vertical to horizontal displacement spreads",
      "atomics": [
        "Use grazing incidence geometry to project angular displacements to linear displacements",
        "Compute ratio as cotangent of incident angle: r = cot(θ)",
        "Substitute θ=3° and evaluate numerically"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify result makes physical sense: at very shallow angles, geometry compresses horizontal more than vertical",
    "Round result to nearest whole number",
    "Confirm answer represents ratio of vertical extent divided by horizontal extent"
  ]
}

Candidate v2 gold_actions:
{
  "global": "Use ray tracing and Snell's law analogs to compute how reflected moonlight spreads vertically versus horizontally across the rippled surface.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Set incident ray at θ=3° and compute reflection law effects from surface perturbations",
      "atomics": [
        "Incident ray direction: (cos(3°), 0, sin(3°))",
        "Surface normal for ripple slope dh/dx: (-dh/dx, 0, 1)",
        "Reflected ray direction: d_i - 2(d_i·n)n, showing z-component change ≈ -2sin(θ)dh/dx"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Constrain ripples by requiring reflected rays remain upward-traveling",
      "atomics": [
        "Reflected ray z-component = sin(θ) - 2sin(θ)dh/dx must be > 0",
        "Maximum ripple slope: dh/dx < θ/2 ≈ 0.026 radians",
        "Angular deviation range: from θ to 0 (maximum compression of vertical spreading)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Account for different geometric projections in vertical versus horizontal directions",
      "atomics": [
        "For vertical ripples in x-z plane: angular spread Δα_z ≈ θ (full range from 0 to θ)",
        "For horizontal ripples in y-z plane: angular spread Δα_y ≈ 2sin(θ)·max_slope ≈ θ",
        "Vertical linear extent at grazing incidence ∝ Δα_z / tan(θ)",
        "Horizontal linear extent at grazing incidence ∝ Δα_y / 1 (less compressed)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Compute final ratio r = cot(3°)",
      "atomics": [
        "Calculate tan(3°) = tan(0.05236 rad) ≈ 0.05241",
        "Compute r = 1/tan(3°) = cot(3°) ≈ 19.08",
        "Round to nearest integer: r = 19"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": []
}

Output the JSON verdict now.

